<br>
Anyway... now that I read most of the thread...<br>
<br>
One thing that is being missed, with the whole idea of banning guns... is that a gun is not really all that hard to make these days.  I mean really, some of the best guns (best as in, most concealed) for doing damage were hand made.  Sure, right now it's a heck of a lot easier to buy a ready-made gun.  But when gunsmiths were just cranking up, it wasn't uncommon to have handmade guns (rifles mostly).  If you outlawed them, it wouldn't take long for someone to start making illegal ones.  With the possible exception of the rifling, there's nothing complex about a gun.<br>
<br>
Tubing, gunpowder, ball bearings, striker.<br>
<br>
Might not be a M-16, but as stated earlier... fully automatic weapons are almost never used in shootings.  The most common are still revolvers (very cheap compared to semi-automatic pistols).<br>
<br>
And we are focusing on homicides, which as stated above really isn't a significant danger to most people, unless you happen to live in Washington D.C. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Even in NYC, if you take some precautions your chances are pretty good you'll never get shot.  Now, if you happen to flip off a bunch of gang members and call them f*'ing spics... you probably won't live long.<br>
<br>
It has been shown over and over that criminals, for the most part, are chicken-shits.  If they think there is a good chance you have a gun, they will almost definately avoid you.<br>
<br>
It's a simple fact... freedom will mean we have to deal with some stuff.  As much as liberals don't want to hear it... those of us that like our freedom accept that there are some drawbacks.  .7% deathrate from gun deaths is &quot;acceptable losses&quot; compared to losing our freedom to own guns.<br>
<br>
Anyway, as been stated... odds are that only a very small percentage of those gundeaths wouldn't be converted to &quot;knife/bludgening&quot; deaths.<br>
<br>
As much as the movies like to portray inner-city gangs running around with M-16's, AK-47's and Submachine guns... it just isn't the case most of the time.<br>
<br>
Also, how many of those deaths are gang-related, especially in the big cities?  Having a bunch of kids shooting each other of which color they are wearing doesn't really affect you and I (unless you kid is in a gang... and if that's the case... MOVE)<br>
<br>
Anyway, people that don't know anything about guns are generally the ones the most opposed to them.  They just see them as a pointless item that causes harm.  Usually they are moved by sad stories, like that of Bradley, about how they got shot and how tragic it is.<br>
<br>
Guns are not the problem... we live in a pretty violent society, taking guns away won't do anything to change that.  Actually it creates more violence because people feel their freedoms being taken away.  Though Americans are more and more getting desensitised to having their freedoms taken away, there is still a lot of us that believe freedom is above all else.<br>
<br>
We don't want to live in the UK... if we did, we'd move.  We like living in the US, and that means freedom, and that means the Bill of Rights.  The goverment has been thrashing at the Bill of Rights a lot lately, and this one is just easier to see.<br>
